Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE I/O - Convenience Wrappers Over io_core File Operations
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Higher-level file I/O primitives layered on top of io_core. The io_core
Note: module exposes raw handles and byte buffers; this module exposes the
Note: idiomatic "read whole file as string" / "write string to file" /
Note: "append" / "line iteration" calls that the rest of the compiler reaches
Note: for. Built on direct Linux syscalls (read=0, write=1, open=2, close=3)
Note: through the existing runtime entry points.

Note: Conventions:
Note:   - Path arguments are null-terminated C strings (Integer pointers).
Note:   - Return type Integer for content reads holds a pointer to a
Note:     null-terminated heap-allocated buffer; caller takes ownership.
Note:   - All write operations return bytes-written on success or a negative
Note:     errno value on failure.
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall

Note: ============================================================================
Note: OPEN MODE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Mirror the POSIX O_* flags used by the open(2) syscall. Combine with
Note: bitwise OR for compound modes (e.g. write_create_truncate).

Constant FILE_MODE_READ_ONLY as Integer is 0
Constant FILE_MODE_WRITE_ONLY as Integer is 1
Constant FILE_MODE_READ_WRITE as Integer is 2
Constant FILE_MODE_CREATE as Integer is 64
Constant FILE_MODE_EXCLUSIVE as Integer is 128
Constant FILE_MODE_TRUNCATE as Integer is 512
Constant FILE_MODE_APPEND as Integer is 1024

Note: Default permissions for newly-created files (0644 - owner read+write,
Note: group/other read-only).
Constant FILE_DEFAULT_PERMS as Integer is 420

Note: Maximum file size accepted by read_entire_file. Files larger than this
Note: are rejected to prevent unbounded memory allocation during compiler runs.
Constant FILE_MAX_SIZE as Integer is 134217728

Note: getcwd syscall number on Linux x86_64. The platform-aware syscall router
Note: maps this to the correct instruction (or equivalent call) on other targets.
Constant SYS_GETCWD as Integer is 79

Note: Buffer size for get_cwd_internal, set to the Linux PATH_MAX. Any legal
Note: absolute path fits within this bound, including its trailing null terminator.
Constant PATH_BUFFER_SIZE as Integer is 4096

Note: mkdir and unlink syscall numbers on Linux x86_64. The platform-aware
Note: syscall router maps these to the correct instruction (or equivalent call)
Note: on other targets.
Constant SYS_MKDIR as Integer is 83
Constant SYS_UNLINK as Integer is 87

Note: Default directory permissions for created directories (0755 octal = 493).
Constant DIR_DEFAULT_PERMS as Integer is 493

Note: stat, rmdir, and getdents64 syscall numbers on Linux x86_64. The
Note: platform-aware syscall router maps these to the correct instruction (or
Note: equivalent call) on other targets. stat fills a struct stat buffer for a
Note: path; rmdir removes an empty directory; getdents64 reads directory entries
Note: from an open directory file descriptor into a caller buffer.
Constant SYS_STAT as Integer is 4
Constant SYS_RMDIR as Integer is 84
Constant SYS_GETDENTS64 as Integer is 217

Note: Size of the Linux x86_64 struct stat (144 bytes). stat writes the file
Note: metadata into a buffer of at least this size.
Constant STAT_STRUCT_SIZE as Integer is 144

Note: Byte offset of the st_mode field within struct stat on Linux x86_64. The
Note: field is a 32-bit mode word combining the file-type bits (S_IFMT) and the
Note: permission bits.
Constant STAT_ST_MODE_OFFSET as Integer is 24

Note: File-type mask (S_IFMT = 0o170000 = 61440) and the directory type value
Note: (S_IFDIR = 0o040000 = 16384). (st_mode AND S_IFMT) is equal to S_IFDIR
Note: exactly when the path names a directory.
Constant STAT_S_IFMT as Integer is 61440
Constant STAT_S_IFDIR as Integer is 16384

Note: linux_dirent64 field offsets used while walking getdents64 output. Each
Note: record is variable length: d_ino (8 bytes), d_off (8 bytes), d_reclen
Note: (2-byte record length at offset 16), d_type (1 byte at offset 18), and the
Note: null-terminated d_name beginning at offset 19. d_type value 4 (DT_DIR)
Note: marks a subdirectory.
Constant DIRENT_RECLEN_OFFSET as Integer is 16
Constant DIRENT_DTYPE_OFFSET as Integer is 18
Constant DIRENT_DNAME_OFFSET as Integer is 19
Constant DIRENT_DT_DIR as Integer is 4

Note: Buffer size for a single getdents64 read pass. A directory is drained by
Note: repeatedly filling this buffer until getdents64 returns 0 (end of stream).
Constant DIRENT_BUFFER_SIZE as Integer is 8192

Note: Buffer size for the copy_file read/write loop. Content is streamed through
Note: a fixed stack-free heap buffer so arbitrarily large files copy in bounded
Note: memory.
Constant COPY_BUFFER_SIZE as Integer is 65536

Note: O_RDONLY / O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC mode words for copy_file, plus the
Note: O_DIRECTORY flag (0o200000 = 65536) used when opening a directory for
Note: getdents64 enumeration.
Constant FILE_FLAGS_WRITE_CREATE_TRUNC as Integer is 577
Constant FILE_FLAG_DIRECTORY as Integer is 65536

Note: Negated EINTR (interrupted system call = 4 on Linux). A read or write that
Note: returns this should be retried rather than treated as a hard failure.
Constant FILE_NEG_EINTR as Integer is -4

Note: Negated errno for "file already exists" (EEXIST = 17 on Linux). mkdir
Note: returns this when a path component already exists, which recursive
Note: directory creation treats as success for that component.
Constant FILE_NEG_EEXIST as Integer is -17

Note: Byte value of the path separator '/'.
Constant PATH_SEPARATOR_BYTE as Integer is 47

Note: clock_gettime syscall number on Linux x86_64, with CLOCK_REALTIME as the
Note: wall-clock clock id. The platform-aware syscall router maps the number to
Note: the correct instruction (or equivalent call) on other targets.
Constant SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME as Integer is 228
Constant CLOCK_REALTIME_ID as Integer is 0

Note: Size in bytes of a TimeSpec (8-byte seconds field followed by an 8-byte
Note: nanoseconds field).
Constant TIMESPEC_SIZE as Integer is 16

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SYSCALL WRAPPERS
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Direct Linux x86_64 syscall numbers. Other platforms route through the
Note: platform-aware syscall router at compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa.

Process called "fio_syscall0" takes syscall_num as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Zero-argument syscall (close, etc.)
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "fio_syscall1" takes syscall_num as Integer, arg1 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: One-argument syscall. Dispatched through the platform router so the
    Note: same code works on Linux/Darwin/BSD/Windows targets without change.
    Return syscall_1 from Syscall with syscall_num, arg1
End Process

Process called "fio_syscall2" takes syscall_num as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Two-argument syscall, used by getcwd(buf, size). Dispatched through the
    Note: platform router so the same code resolves to the correct platform
    Note: syscall instruction across Linux/Darwin/BSD/Windows targets.
    Return syscall_2 from Syscall with syscall_num, arg1, arg2
End Process

Process called "fio_syscall3" takes syscall_num as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Three-argument syscall, used by open(path, flags, mode) and the
    Note: read/write/pread/pwrite family. The router resolves syscall_num
    Note: to the correct platform syscall instruction (or simulated path
    Note: on platforms that don't expose syscall directly, like Windows
    Note: where it maps to a NTDLL Nt* call).
    Return syscall_3 from Syscall with syscall_num, arg1, arg2, arg3
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BASIC FILE OPERATIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Open a file by path with the given combined mode flags. Returns the file
Note: descriptor on success, or a negative errno on failure.
Note: For read-only access prefer open_read; for fresh writes prefer
Note: open_write_truncate; for log-style writes prefer open_append.
Process called "fio_open" takes path as Integer, flags as Integer, perms as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: syscall 2 = open on x86_64 Linux. The runtime dispatches by number.
    Let fd be fio_syscall3(2, path, flags, perms)
    Return fd
End Process

Note: Open for reading. Fails (negative return) if the path doesn't exist.
Process called "fio_open_read" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Return fio_open(path, FILE_MODE_READ_ONLY, 0)
End Process

Note: Open for writing, creating the file if missing and truncating to zero
Note: length if it exists. Permissions default to 0644.
Process called "fio_open_write_truncate" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Let flags be FILE_MODE_WRITE_ONLY plus FILE_MODE_CREATE
    Set flags to flags plus FILE_MODE_TRUNCATE
    Return fio_open(path, flags, FILE_DEFAULT_PERMS)
End Process

Note: Open for appending. Creates the file if missing. Writes always land
Note: at end-of-file regardless of seek position.
Process called "fio_open_append" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Let flags be FILE_MODE_WRITE_ONLY plus FILE_MODE_CREATE
    Set flags to flags plus FILE_MODE_APPEND
    Return fio_open(path, flags, FILE_DEFAULT_PERMS)
End Process

Note: Close a previously-opened file descriptor. Returns 0 on success.
Process called "fio_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Return fio_syscall1(3, fd)
End Process

Note: Read up to count bytes from fd into buffer. Returns bytes actually read
Note: (0 = EOF, negative = error).
Process called "fio_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Return fio_syscall3(0, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Note: Write count bytes from buffer to fd. Returns bytes actually written.
Note: Short writes are possible - callers should loop until count is fully
Note: written or an error is reported.
Process called "fio_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Return fio_syscall3(1, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Note: Reposition the file offset. whence: 0 = SEEK_SET, 1 = SEEK_CUR, 2 = SEEK_END.
Process called "fio_seek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Return fio_syscall3(8, fd, offset, whence)
End Process

Note: Return current file length by seeking to end and back to start.
Note: Returns -1 on error.
Process called "fio_file_length" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Let length be fio_seek(fd, 0, 2)
    If length is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let restore be fio_seek(fd, 0, 0)
    If restore is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return length
End Process

Note: Return the process's current working directory as a freshly allocated,
Note: null-terminated absolute path string. Returns 0 on failure.
Note: Caller takes ownership of the returned buffer.
Note: Implemented via the getcwd syscall (x86_64 number 79), routed through the
Note: platform-aware syscall layer. The kernel writes the absolute path into the
Note: caller-supplied buffer and returns the number of bytes written including
Note: the trailing null on success, or a negative errno on failure (most commonly
Note: -ERANGE when the buffer is too small for the path). PATH_BUFFER_SIZE is set
Note: to the Linux PATH_MAX (4096), which bounds any legal absolute path.
Process called "get_cwd_internal" returns Integer:
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with PATH_BUFFER_SIZE
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let result be fio_syscall2(SYS_GETCWD, buffer, PATH_BUFFER_SIZE)
    If result is less than 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
        Return 0
    End If
    Return buffer
End Process

Note: Delete a file by path via the unlink syscall. Returns 1 on success, 0 on
Note: failure (for example, the path does not exist or is a directory). A 0 path
Note: is treated as failure.
Process called "delete_file" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    If path is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let result be fio_syscall1(SYS_UNLINK, path)
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: Create a directory and every missing parent directory along its path,
Note: equivalent to "mkdir -p". Returns 1 once the full directory exists, 0 on
Note: failure. Each path component is created with 0755 permissions; a component
Note: that already exists (EEXIST) is accepted and traversal continues. A leading
Note: '/' (absolute path) is handled correctly, and a trailing '/' is tolerated.
Process called "create_directory_recursive" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    If path is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let path_len be proc string_length from StringCore with path
    If path_len is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Work in a private buffer so the caller's string is never mutated. The
    Note: extra byte holds the trailing null terminator for each prefix probe.
    Let work be proc allocate from Layout with path_len plus 1
    If work is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let copy_index be 0
    While copy_index is less than path_len:
        Let src_byte be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with path, copy_index
        proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with work, copy_index, src_byte
        Set copy_index to copy_index plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with work, path_len, 0

    Note: Create each intermediate directory. Start at index 1 so a leading
    Note: separator (root of an absolute path) is not treated as an empty
    Note: component to create.
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than path_len:
        Let current_byte be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with work, i
        If current_byte is equal to PATH_SEPARATOR_BYTE:
            Note: Temporarily terminate the prefix at this separator, create it,
            Note: then restore the separator so the next iteration sees the full
            Note: working path again.
            proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with work, i, 0
            Let prefix_result be fio_syscall2(SYS_MKDIR, work, DIR_DEFAULT_PERMS)
            If prefix_result is less than 0:
                If prefix_result is not equal to FILE_NEG_EEXIST:
                    proc deallocate from Layout with work
                    Return 0
                End If
            End If
            proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with work, i, PATH_SEPARATOR_BYTE
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Create the final (deepest) directory component.
    Let final_result be fio_syscall2(SYS_MKDIR, work, DIR_DEFAULT_PERMS)
    proc deallocate from Layout with work
    If final_result is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If final_result is equal to FILE_NEG_EEXIST:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EXTENDED FILESYSTEM OPERATIONS (stat, copy, recursive directory)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Return 1 if path exists and is a directory, 0 otherwise. Implemented via
Note: the stat syscall into a struct stat buffer; the st_mode field is masked
Note: with S_IFMT and compared against S_IFDIR. A 0 path, a stat failure (the
Note: path does not exist or is unreachable), or any non-directory file type all
Note: yield 0. The scratch buffer is freed before returning.
Process called "directory_exists" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    If path is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let stat_buf be proc allocate from Layout with STAT_STRUCT_SIZE
    If stat_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let result be fio_syscall3(SYS_STAT, path, stat_buf, 0)
    If result is less than 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with stat_buf
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mode be proc memory_get_int32 from MemoryCore with stat_buf, STAT_ST_MODE_OFFSET
    proc deallocate from Layout with stat_buf
    Let file_type be mode bit_and STAT_S_IFMT
    If file_type is equal to STAT_S_IFDIR:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: Return the directory the system uses for temporary files as a freshly
Note: allocated, null-terminated, caller-owned string. The lightweight frontend
Note: substrate has no working getenv (the process-environment callback is wired
Note: only in the full runtime), so TMPDIR cannot be consulted here; the POSIX
Note: default of "/tmp" is the correct, reliable fallback for every Linux/BSD/
Note: Darwin host the compiler frontend runs on. A private copy is returned so
Note: callers may free it without disturbing any shared literal.
Process called "get_temp_dir" returns Integer:
    Let default_dir be "/tmp"
    Let dir_len be proc string_length from StringCore with default_dir
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with dir_len plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with buffer, default_dir, dir_len
    proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with buffer, dir_len, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

Note: Copy the regular file at src to dst, creating or truncating dst. Returns 0
Note: on success, a negative errno on failure. src is opened O_RDONLY; dst is
Note: opened O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC with 0644 permissions. Content streams
Note: through a fixed 64 KiB heap buffer so files of any size copy in bounded
Note: memory. Each write is looped until the full chunk lands (handling short
Note: writes), and both read and write retry on EINTR. Both descriptors and the
Note: buffer are released on every exit path.
Process called "copy_file" takes src as Integer, dst as Integer returns Integer:
    If src is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If dst is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let src_fd be fio_open(src, FILE_MODE_READ_ONLY, 0)
    If src_fd is less than 0:
        Return src_fd
    End If
    Let dst_fd be fio_open(dst, FILE_FLAGS_WRITE_CREATE_TRUNC, FILE_DEFAULT_PERMS)
    If dst_fd is less than 0:
        Let close_src be fio_close(src_fd)
        Return dst_fd
    End If
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with COPY_BUFFER_SIZE
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Let close_src2 be fio_close(src_fd)
        Let close_dst2 be fio_close(dst_fd)
        Return -1
    End If

    Let status be 0
    Let copying be 1
    While copying is equal to 1:
        Let bytes_read be fio_read(src_fd, buffer, COPY_BUFFER_SIZE)
        If bytes_read is less than 0:
            If bytes_read is equal to FILE_NEG_EINTR:
                Note: Interrupted before any data transferred; the enclosing loop
                Note: re-issues the read on the next iteration (retry on EINTR).
                Set copying to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set status to bytes_read
                Set copying to 0
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If bytes_read is equal to 0:
                Note: End of source file reached.
                Set copying to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let written be 0
                Let write_ok be 1
                While written is less than bytes_read:
                    Let remaining be bytes_read minus written
                    Let chunk be fio_write(dst_fd, buffer plus written, remaining)
                    If chunk is less than 0:
                        If chunk is equal to FILE_NEG_EINTR:
                            Note: Interrupted before progress; the inner loop
                            Note: re-issues the write (retry on EINTR). written is
                            Note: left unchanged so the same span is rewritten.
                            Set write_ok to 1
                        Otherwise:
                            Set status to chunk
                            Set write_ok to 0
                            Set written to bytes_read
                        End If
                    Otherwise:
                        If chunk is equal to 0:
                            Note: No progress and no error: treat as a write
                            Note: failure to avoid an infinite loop.
                            Set status to -1
                            Set write_ok to 0
                            Set written to bytes_read
                        Otherwise:
                            Set written to written plus chunk
                        End If
                    End If
                End While
                If write_ok is equal to 0:
                    Set copying to 0
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
    Let close_src3 be fio_close(src_fd)
    Let close_dst3 be fio_close(dst_fd)
    Return status
End Process

Note: Recursively remove the directory at path and everything beneath it.
Note: Returns 0 on success, a negative errno on the first failure encountered.
Note: The directory is opened with O_RDONLY|O_DIRECTORY and drained with
Note: getdents64; "." and ".." are skipped. Each entry's absolute child path is
Note: built (path + "/" + name); subdirectories recurse through delete_directory
Note: and regular entries are unlinked. After the directory is emptied its
Note: descriptor is closed and rmdir removes the now-empty directory itself. All
Note: heap buffers are freed on every path.
Process called "delete_directory" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    If path is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let dir_fd be fio_open(path, FILE_FLAG_DIRECTORY, 0)
    If dir_fd is less than 0:
        Return dir_fd
    End If
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with DIRENT_BUFFER_SIZE
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Let close_fd be fio_close(dir_fd)
        Return -1
    End If

    Let status be 0
    Let reading be 1
    While reading is equal to 1:
        Let nread be fio_syscall3(SYS_GETDENTS64, dir_fd, buffer, DIRENT_BUFFER_SIZE)
        If nread is less than 0:
            If nread is equal to FILE_NEG_EINTR:
                Note: Interrupted; the enclosing loop re-issues getdents64 on the
                Note: next iteration (retry on EINTR).
                Set reading to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set status to nread
                Set reading to 0
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If nread is equal to 0:
                Note: All entries consumed.
                Set reading to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let offset be 0
                While offset is less than nread:
                    Let reclen be proc memory_get_int16 from MemoryCore with buffer, offset plus DIRENT_RECLEN_OFFSET
                    Let dtype be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with buffer, offset plus DIRENT_DTYPE_OFFSET
                    Let name_ptr be buffer plus offset plus DIRENT_DNAME_OFFSET
                    Let skip be proc dirent_is_dot_entry with name_ptr
                    If skip is equal to 0:
                        Let child be proc join_path with path, name_ptr
                        If child is equal to 0:
                            Set status to -1
                            Set offset to nread
                            Set reading to 0
                        Otherwise:
                            If dtype is equal to DIRENT_DT_DIR:
                                Let sub_status be proc delete_directory with child
                                If sub_status is less than 0:
                                    Set status to sub_status
                                End If
                            Otherwise:
                                Let unlink_result be fio_syscall1(SYS_UNLINK, child)
                                If unlink_result is less than 0:
                                    Set status to unlink_result
                                End If
                            End If
                            proc deallocate from Layout with child
                        End If
                    End If
                    If reclen is less than 1:
                        Note: A zero record length would loop forever; abort
                        Note: this buffer to preserve forward progress.
                        Set offset to nread
                    Otherwise:
                        Set offset to offset plus reclen
                    End If
                End While
                If status is less than 0:
                    Set reading to 0
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
    Let close_dir be fio_close(dir_fd)
    If status is less than 0:
        Return status
    End If
    Let rmdir_result be fio_syscall1(SYS_RMDIR, path)
    If rmdir_result is less than 0:
        Return rmdir_result
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: Recursively copy the directory tree at src into dst. Returns 0 on success,
Note: a negative errno on the first failure. dst (and any missing parents) is
Note: created via create_directory_recursive. src is opened with
Note: O_RDONLY|O_DIRECTORY and walked with getdents64; "." and ".." are skipped.
Note: For each entry the source and destination child paths are built; a
Note: subdirectory recurses through copy_directory, a regular entry is copied
Note: with copy_file. All heap buffers are freed on every path.
Process called "copy_directory" takes src as Integer, dst as Integer returns Integer:
    If src is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If dst is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let made be proc create_directory_recursive with dst
    If made is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let dir_fd be fio_open(src, FILE_FLAG_DIRECTORY, 0)
    If dir_fd is less than 0:
        Return dir_fd
    End If
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with DIRENT_BUFFER_SIZE
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Let close_fd be fio_close(dir_fd)
        Return -1
    End If

    Let status be 0
    Let reading be 1
    While reading is equal to 1:
        Let nread be fio_syscall3(SYS_GETDENTS64, dir_fd, buffer, DIRENT_BUFFER_SIZE)
        If nread is less than 0:
            If nread is equal to FILE_NEG_EINTR:
                Note: Interrupted; the enclosing loop re-issues getdents64 on the
                Note: next iteration (retry on EINTR).
                Set reading to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set status to nread
                Set reading to 0
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If nread is equal to 0:
                Note: All entries consumed.
                Set reading to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let offset be 0
                While offset is less than nread:
                    Let reclen be proc memory_get_int16 from MemoryCore with buffer, offset plus DIRENT_RECLEN_OFFSET
                    Let dtype be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with buffer, offset plus DIRENT_DTYPE_OFFSET
                    Let name_ptr be buffer plus offset plus DIRENT_DNAME_OFFSET
                    Let skip be proc dirent_is_dot_entry with name_ptr
                    If skip is equal to 0:
                        Let src_child be proc join_path with src, name_ptr
                        Let dst_child be proc join_path with dst, name_ptr
                        If src_child is equal to 0:
                            Set status to -1
                            Set offset to nread
                            Set reading to 0
                        Otherwise:
                            If dst_child is equal to 0:
                                proc deallocate from Layout with src_child
                                Set status to -1
                                Set offset to nread
                                Set reading to 0
                            Otherwise:
                                If dtype is equal to DIRENT_DT_DIR:
                                    Let sub_status be proc copy_directory with src_child, dst_child
                                    If sub_status is less than 0:
                                        Set status to sub_status
                                    End If
                                Otherwise:
                                    Let copy_status be proc copy_file with src_child, dst_child
                                    If copy_status is less than 0:
                                        Set status to copy_status
                                    End If
                                End If
                                proc deallocate from Layout with src_child
                                proc deallocate from Layout with dst_child
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                    If reclen is less than 1:
                        Note: Guard against a zero record length looping forever.
                        Set offset to nread
                    Otherwise:
                        Set offset to offset plus reclen
                    End If
                End While
                If status is less than 0:
                    Set reading to 0
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
    Let close_dir be fio_close(dir_fd)
    Return status
End Process

Note: Return 1 if the null-terminated name pointed to by name_ptr is exactly "."
Note: or "..", 0 otherwise. Used to skip the self/parent directory entries that
Note: getdents64 reports so recursive walks never ascend or loop on themselves.
Process called "dirent_is_dot_entry" takes name_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let first be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with name_ptr, 0
    If first is not equal to 46:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let second be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with name_ptr, 1
    If second is equal to 0:
        Note: name is "."
        Return 1
    End If
    If second is equal to 46:
        Let third be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with name_ptr, 2
        If third is equal to 0:
            Note: name is ".."
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: Build a freshly allocated, null-terminated, caller-owned path by joining a
Note: directory string and a child name with a single '/' separator
Note: ("dir" + "/" + "name"). The directory's own length is used verbatim, so a
Note: trailing separator on dir would produce a doubled separator; callers in
Note: this module pass clean directory paths. Returns 0 if either argument is 0
Note: or allocation fails.
Process called "join_path" takes dir as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    If dir is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dir_len be proc string_length from StringCore with dir
    Let name_len be proc string_length from StringCore with name
    Let total be dir_len plus name_len plus 1
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with total plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with buffer, dir, dir_len
    proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with buffer, dir_len, PATH_SEPARATOR_BYTE
    proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with buffer plus dir_len plus 1, name, name_len
    proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with buffer, total, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

Note: Return the current wall-clock time as whole seconds since the Unix epoch.
Note: Implemented via clock_gettime(CLOCK_REALTIME) into a 16-byte TimeSpec, then
Note: reading the seconds field (offset 0). Returns 0 if the clock query fails or
Note: the scratch buffer cannot be allocated. The unit matches the modification
Note: time reported by the file metadata layer, so the two are directly
Note: comparable for staleness checks.
Process called "get_current_time_seconds" returns Integer:
    Let timespec be proc allocate from Layout with TIMESPEC_SIZE
    If timespec is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let result be fio_syscall2(SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME, CLOCK_REALTIME_ID, timespec)
    If result is less than 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with timespec
        Return 0
    End If
    Let seconds be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with timespec, 0
    proc deallocate from Layout with timespec
    Return seconds
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIGH-LEVEL CONVENIENCE WRAPPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Read the entire contents of a file as a null-terminated string. Allocates
Note: a fresh buffer sized to file length + 1. Returns 0 on error.
Note: Caller takes ownership of the returned buffer.
Process called "read_entire_file" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fd be fio_open_read(path)
    If fd is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let length be fio_file_length(fd)
    If length is less than 0:
        Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is greater than FILE_MAX_SIZE:
        Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with length plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let total_read be 0
    Let remaining be length
    While remaining is greater than 0:
        Let chunk be fio_read(fd, buffer plus total_read, remaining)
        If chunk is less than 0:
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
            Return 0
        End If
        If chunk is equal to 0:
            Set remaining to 0
        Otherwise:
            Set total_read to total_read plus chunk
            Set remaining to remaining minus chunk
        End If
    End While

    Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
    Note: null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with buffer, total_read, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

Note: Write content (a null-terminated string) to path, replacing any existing
Note: contents. Creates the file if missing. Returns bytes written on success,
Note: or a negative value on failure.
Process called "write_entire_file" takes path as Integer, content as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fd be fio_open_write_truncate(path)
    If fd is less than 0:
        Return fd
    End If

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with content
    Let total_written be 0
    While total_written is less than length:
        Let remaining be length minus total_written
        Let chunk be fio_write(fd, content plus total_written, remaining)
        If chunk is less than 0:
            Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
            Return chunk
        End If
        If chunk is equal to 0:
            Set total_written to length
        Otherwise:
            Set total_written to total_written plus chunk
        End If
    End While

    Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
    Return total_written
End Process

Note: Append content to the end of path. Creates the file if missing.
Note: Returns bytes written.
Process called "append_to_file" takes path as Integer, content as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fd be fio_open_append(path)
    If fd is less than 0:
        Return fd
    End If

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with content
    Let total_written be 0
    While total_written is less than length:
        Let remaining be length minus total_written
        Let chunk be fio_write(fd, content plus total_written, remaining)
        If chunk is less than 0:
            Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
            Return chunk
        End If
        If chunk is equal to 0:
            Set total_written to length
        Otherwise:
            Set total_written to total_written plus chunk
        End If
    End While

    Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
    Return total_written
End Process

Note: True (1) if the path can be opened for reading.
Process called "file_readable" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fd be fio_open_read(path)
    If fd is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let close_result be fio_close(fd)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LINE-ORIENTED HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Locate the byte offset of the next newline (0x0A) starting from offset
Note: in buffer of total length len. Returns the offset of the newline, or
Note: len if no newline is found.
Process called "find_next_newline" takes buffer as Integer, offset as Integer, len as Integer returns Integer:
    Let i be offset
    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with buffer, i
        If ch is equal to 10:
            Return i
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return len
End Process

Note: Count the number of lines in a string (newline-terminated regions). A
Note: file with no trailing newline still counts the trailing fragment.
Process called "count_lines" takes content as Integer returns Integer:
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with content
    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with content, i
        If ch is equal to 10:
            Note: Don't count trailing newline as a separate empty line.
            If i is less than length minus 1:
                Set count to count plus 1
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return count
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PATH UTILITIES
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Return 1 if path begins with '/' (absolute Unix path) or 'X:' (Windows).
Process called "is_absolute_path" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    If path is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let first be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with path, 0
    If first is equal to 47:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: Windows drive letter form like "C:\..."
    Let second be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with path, 1
    If second is equal to 58:
        If first is greater than or equal to 65:
            If first is less than or equal to 90:
                Return 1
            End If
            If first is greater than or equal to 97:
                If first is less than or equal to 122:
                    Return 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: Find the byte offset of the last directory separator ('/' or '\') in
Note: path. Returns -1 if no separator is present.
Process called "last_separator_offset" takes path as Integer returns Integer:
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with path
    Let last be -1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with path, i
        If ch is equal to 47:
            Set last to i
        End If
        If ch is equal to 92:
            Set last to i
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return last
End Process
